        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Capital gains tax on an off-the-plan property is calculated from the date the original contract was signed, not the settlement date. If more than twelve months passed between signing the contract and settlement, the seller is typically entitled to the 50% CGT discount on any capital gain. However, if the property is sold before settlement via contract assignment, the CGT event is triggered at the assignment date. The specifics of your situation should be confirmed with a tax professional, as individual circumstances vary."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between selling an off-the-plan apartment and a standard resale?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "An off-the-plan property sold before settlement involves the transfer of a contract right, not the transfer of a title. A standard resale involves the seller transferring registered title at settlement. Post-settlement resale of an off-the-plan property follows the same process as any standard resale, except that the property will likely be newer and may carry developer warranties that transfer to the buyer. The marketing approach and buyer pool are also typically different."
      }
    }
